 surnames such as   Del Cid   and   Del Signore  , has apparently been in some instances counted as an independent surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Delle","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place so named in North Rhine-Westphalia or a topographic name (see   Dell  ).","French (Lorraine): habitational name from Delle, a place in Territoire de Belfort. Alternatively, a topographic name, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’, for someone who lived near a prominent alder tree or trees, from <i>elle</i>, a derivative of Middle High German <i>erle</i> ‘alder’."]}]},{"name":"Sandes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Sands  .","Galician: habitational name from any of various places so named in Galicia (Spain). Compare   Sandez  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sands","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>sandes</i> ‘sands’, for someone who lived at or near a sandy place, or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Sands in Carlisle (Cumberland) or Sands Cottages in West Hoathly (Sussex). See   Sand  , of which <i>Sands</i> may sometimes be a plural form or a variant, with excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare also   Sandes   and   Sandys  .","History: Comfort Sands, a revolutionary patriot born in 1748 at what is now Sands’ Point, Long Island, NY, was descended from James Sand(y)s (1622–95), who emigrated from Reading, Berkshire, England, to Plymouth, MA, and followed Anne Hutchinson to Westchester County, NY, and subsequently RI. In 1661 he settled on Block Island, RI."]},{"name":"Sandez","meanings":["Galician: variant of   Sandes  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Simon del Sandes was born about 1210 as the son of Walter del Sandes. He had at least 1 son with unknown."},"et":{"about 1210–Deceased":"umbes 1210–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","1237–Male":"1237–Surnud","1187–Male":"1187–Surnud","1237":"1237","1212":"1212","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","about 1210":"umbes 1210"},"fi":{"about 1210–Deceased":"noin 1210–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1212–Female":"1212–Kuollut","1237–Male":"1237–Kuollut","1187–Male":"1187–Kuollut","1237":"1237","1212":"1212","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","about 1210":"noin 1210"},"fr":{"about 1210–Deceased":"environ 1210–Décédé","1210–Male":"1210–Décédé","1212–Female":"1212–Décédée","1237–Male":"1237–Décédé","1187–Male":"1187–Décédé","1237":"1237","1212":"1212","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","about 1210":"environ 1210","lifeSummary":"Simon del Sandes est né environ 1210, fils de Walter del Sandes. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec unknown."},"de":{"about 1210–Deceased":"um 1210–Verstorben","1210–Male":"1210–Verstorben","1212–Female":"1212–Verstorben","1237–Male":"1237–Verstorben","1187–Male":"1187–Verstorben","1237":"1237","1212":"1212","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","about 1210":"um 1210","lifeSummary":"Simon del Sandes wurde um 1210, als Sohn von Walter del Sandes geboren. Er hatte mit unknown mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1210–Deceased":"about 1210–Desede","1210–Male":"1210–Desede","1212–Female":"1212–Desede","1237–Male":"1237–Desede","1187–Male":"1187–Desede",